<TITLE> 'Fantastic' Friday opening: $22.8 million </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 LOS ANGELES, June 17 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - 20th Century Fox's 'Fantastic Four: Rise of the Silver Surfer' doesn't appear to be suffering from any sequel fatigue. The PG-rated, Tim Story-directed follow-up to the 2005 Marvel Comics-based 'Fantastic Four' rode a strong wave at the box office on Friday, opening to an estimated $22.8 million in 3,959 theaters, according to the boxoffice tracking site BoxofficeMojo.com. If it maintains its momentum over the weekend, it could top the opening number posted by the original of $56.1 million. Warner Brothers Pictures' PG-rated teen detective yarn, 'Nancy Drew,' starring Emma Roberts, the weekend's other new wide arrival, was greeted with just an estimated $2.9 million, which left it in virtual dead heat with Sony Pictures' animated 'Surf's Up' for the fifth-place slot. Rounding out the top five, Warners' 'Ocean's Thirteen,' which topped the box office last weekend, took in an estimated $6 million for the day, for a second-place showing. Universal Pictures' relationship comedy 'Knocked Up' was third with an estimated $4.6 million, as its domestic gross climbed above $80 million. Buena Vista's 'Pirates of the Caribbean: At World's End' claimed the fourth spot with an estimated $3.3 milli
